 religious perspectives in order to approximate the living texture of popular religious thought and practice in the United States. The history of religion in America is more than the story of institutions and famous people. This anthology presents a more nuanced story composed of the everyday actions and thoughts of lay men and women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aReligion. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAmerican Jews.  aAmericans.  aAssemblies of God.  aAzusa Street Revival.  aBaptists.  aBenediction of the Blessed Sacrament.  aBible story.  aBook of Mormon.  aBuddhism.  aCatechism.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholicism.  aCentral Conference of American Rabbis.  aCeremony.  aChristian.  aChristianity and Islam.  aChristianity.  aChurch service.  aCivil religion.  aConsecration.  aConversion to Judaism.  aDispensationalist theology.  aDua.  aEucharist.  aExaltation (Mormonism).  aFollow the Prophet.  aGod.  aHaggadah.  aHeathenry (new religious movement).  aHinduism.  aInternational Church of the Foursquare Gospel.  aIslam in the United States.  aJehovah's Witnesses.  aJesus the Christ (book).  aJews.  aJudaism.  aJustification (theology).  aKatherine Mayo.  aLiberation theology.  aLord's Prayer.  aMahayana.  aMary Baker Eddy.  aMatzo.  aMethodism.  aMinister (Christianity).  aMitzvah.  aMonstrance.  aMormons.  aMuslim.  aNation of Islam.  aNew Testament.  aNew Thought.  aNichiren Buddhism.  aNichiren.  aOn Religion.  aOrdination of women.  aOrdination.  aOregon Catholic Press.  aOrthodox Judaism.  aPastor.  aPentecostalism.  aPeter Cartwright (revivalist).  aPhilosophy of religion.  aPlan of salvation (Latter Day Saints).  aPreacher.  aProtestant Reformers.  aProtestantism.  aProverbs